comment.narrative:
1.	Coordinate and monitor the implementation of the Roadmap for a sustainable solution to the illegal possession, misuse and trafficking of SALW/firearms and their ammunition in the Western Balkans;
2.	Support authorities in the Western Balkans in fully harmonizing their arms control legislation with the Union regulatory framework and other related international obligations; and
3.	Provide support for countering illicit arms trafficking in the Western Balkans, the Republic of Moldova, Ukraine and Belarus through capacity assessments and technical assistance to the law-enforcement and border police authorities.

1. -	Two regional Roadmap coordination meetings organized online due to the COVID 19 limitations (on 3 July, and, on 25-26 November) enabling taking stock of progress, information exchange, knowledge transfer and standardization; 
-	Four informal coordination meetings with implementing partners on selected Roadmap areas were organized in advance of the 4th regional Roadmap meeting to ensure coordination of support provided to the Western Balkans authorities;
-	Nine (9) local coordination meetings chaired by the SALW Commissions were supported in: Albania (17 June, 16 November), Bosnia and Herzegovina (2 June, 20 November), Kosovo (24 June, 5 November), Montenegro (12 November) and North Macedonia (26 June, 10 November);
-	Two regional Roadmap progress reports were prepared, including: a report on progress based on Roadmap Key Performance Indicators (KPIs), a narrative report based on the Roadmap 7 goals, and one report with the activities of the international organizations in the region. 
2. -	A gap analysis of the law on weapons was conducted in Kosovo, while gap analysis of the legal framework on SALW control and civil use of explosives was conducted in North Macedonia.
-	One regional workshop on the harmonization of legislation in the field of SALW and explosives control with EU Acquis was organised via an online platform on 15 December 2020 with participants from Western Balkans, Moldova, Belarus and Ukraine. 
-	One thematic workshop on the Draft law of civil use of explosives and pyrotechnic material organized on 30 October 2020 in North Macedonia.
-	Technical advice on the harmonization of SALW control legal framework with the EU Acquis provided to North Macedonia and Serbia, while advisory support on the development of the new SALW Strategy and Action Plan was provided to Bosnia and Herzegovina. 
-	A Media Strategy Development Programme was completed by the Head of the SALW Commission of Montenegro.
3. -	A detailed needs assessment of the border authorities’ capacities in five Western Balkans jurisdictions was finalized and the reports outlining the main findings and recommendations were endorsed at a Regional Border Police meeting, organized on 1 December 2020.
-	Methodology for conducting the needs assessment of the capacities of the criminal police services was developed by SEESAC, and experts to be deployed to conduct the assessment were recruited; 
-	A five-day Open Source Intelligence Training with six Western Balkans jurisdictions, Belarus, Moldova and Ukraine, focusing on increasing the capacity for online investigations by using the open source intelligence tools was organized; 
-	Support was provided for operationalisation of Firearms Focal Points in the Western Balkans;
-	Sharing of information was facilitated through a Regional FFP meeting that facilitated the exchange of experience and best practices regarding the FFPs establishment and operationalization; gathering experts from six Western Balkans jurisdictions and Moldova; 
-	A template SoP for the Firearm Focal Points in SEE was developed to support the jurisdictions in better defining the responsibilities and functioning of the FFPs; 
-	Guideline for tracing of firearms was developed by SEESAC, in order to support the jurisdictions’ FFPs in drafting bylaws, which further support a more effective tracing of the firearms; 
-	Support in reducing the backlog of unregistered weapon legalization requests in the IBIS System was provided to Kosovo Forensic Agency

Activity Result 1.1. Coordination of the implementation of the Roadmap for a sustainable solution to the illegal possession, misuse and trafficking of SALW/firearms and their ammunition in the Western Balkans
•	Organization of up to two regional Roadmap coordination meetings;
•	Enabling taking stock of progress, information exchange, knowledge transfer and standardization;
•	Support to organization of local coordination meetings (up to 12 in total);
•	Development of biannual monitoring reports (up to two).
Activity Result 1.2. Support to the authorities of the Western Balkans in fully harmonising their arms control legislation with the Union regulatory framework and other related international obligations and standards across the region
•	Assessment and gap analysis (six) of legal framework reports for each beneficiary;
•	Up to one regional workshop and one thematic workshop for the beneficiaries;
•	Provision of on-demand expertise on legislative and policy updates;
Activity Result 1.3. Countering illicit arms trafficking in the Western Balkans, the Republic of Moldova, Ukraine and Belarus through capacity assessments and technical assistance to the law-enforcement and border police authorities
•	Needs assessment of the border-police of the Western Balkans in countering illicit arms trafficking initiated;

1.1. Roadmap coordination and monitoring conducted through:
- Two regional Roadmap coordination meetings organized in Sarajevo, on 28 May, and in Tirana, on 20-21 November, enabling taking stock of progress, information exchange, knowledge transfer and standardization;
- Two rounds of 6 local coordination meetings held by the SALW Commissions were supported in Belgrade (8 May, 8 November), Podgorica (7 May, 4 November), Pristina (2 April, 30 October), Sarajevo (16 May, 7 November), Skopje (23 April, 29 October) and Tirana (6 May, 1 November);
- Two Roadmap monitoring reports prepared, including a report on the progress of the Roadmap Key Performance Indicators (KPIs), a narrative report based on the Roadmap 7 goals, and one report with the activities of the international organizations in the region;
- Roadmap presented at various international events.
1.2. Western Balkans arms control legal frameworks harmonized through:
- Two gap analyses of the legal framework on SALW and explosives control compared to the relevant EU Directives prepared for Albania and BiH;
- Gap analyses of the legal frameworks on SALW control compared to the relevant EU Directives prepared in Serbia, Montenegro and Kosovo;
- One regional workshop dealing with the harmonization of legislation in the field of SALW and explosives ( including explosive precursors) control with EU Acquis organised in Podgorica, on 17-18 September;
- Four workshops on the harmonization of the SALW control legal framework organized in Sarajevo (16-17 April and on 24-25 June), Belgrade (5-6 September), and Podgorica (2-3 December);
- Technical and advisory support provided on the harmonization of the SALW control legal framework in BiH and Serbia with the EU Acquis;
- One media strategy development training completed by the Head of the SALW Coordination Board in BiH.
1.3. Strengthened countering illicit arms trafficking in the Western Balkans, the Republic of Moldova, Ukraine and Belarus, through:
- Needs assessments of the border-police in countering illicit arms trafficking initiated with field missions conducted in Serbia (28 October – 1 November), Montenegro (5-8 November), Kosovo (11-14 November), Albania (19-22 November) and North Macedonia (2-6 December);
- Assessment of the Republic of Moldova, Ukraine and Belarus for selected aspects of SALW control initiated through the participation of representative from the three jurisdictions at the three jurisdictions at the SALW Commissions meeting, the SEEFEN meetings and the regional harmonization workshop. Advisory support to the MoI of Moldova in drafting the Law on the Civil Use of Explosives was also provided.

